      <title>How Do Computers Work?</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/how-computers/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 13 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/how-computers/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Computers feel like magic… but they’re actually &lt;strong&gt;super fast rule-followers&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A computer doesn’t “think” like a human.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;It follows instructions &lt;strong&gt;very, very fast&lt;/strong&gt; — using electricity and tiny switches.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-computers-speak-one-simple-language-1s-and-0s&#34;&gt;1) Computers speak ONE simple language: &lt;strong&gt;1s and 0s&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Inside a computer, everything becomes:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1 = ON&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;0 = OFF&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;That’s it.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Games, YouTube, homework, Roblox, Minecraft — it all becomes huge patterns of &lt;strong&gt;1s and 0s&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;flow.jpg&#34;&#xA;    alt=&#34;Simple diagram showing input -&amp;gt; CPU -&amp;gt; memory -&amp;gt; output&#34;&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;&#xA;      &lt;p&gt;A computer is basically: Input → Processing → Memory/Storage → Output.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
